### Recursion in C#

Recursion is a technique where a method calls itself to solve a problem by breaking it into smaller subproblems.

### Basic Structure

Every recursive method needs:

1. **Base case** - Condition that stops recursion
2. **Recursive case** - Method calls itself with modified parameters

```csharp
static int Factorial(int n)
{
    if (n <= 1)     // Base case
        return 1;
    return n * Factorial(n - 1);  // Recursive case
}
```

### Classic Examples

**Factorial:**

```csharp
static int Factorial(int n) => n <= 1 ? 1 : n * Factorial(n - 1);
// Factorial(5) = 5 * 4 * 3 * 2 * 1 = 120
```

**Fibonacci:**

```csharp
static int Fibonacci(int n)
{
    if (n <= 1) return n;
    return Fibonacci(n - 1) + Fibonacci(n - 2);
}
```

### Iteration vs Recursion

| Aspect | Iteration | Recursion |
|--------|-----------|-----------|
| Code | Loops (for, while) | Method calls itself |
| Memory | Stack frame reused | New frame per call |
| Performance | Faster, less overhead | Slower for deep recursion |
| Readability | Complex problems verbose | Elegant for certain problems |
| Stack overflow | Never | Possible with deep recursion |

### Tail Recursion

When the recursive call is the last operation:

```csharp
static int FactorialTail(int n, int accumulator = 1)
{
    if (n <= 1) return accumulator;
    return FactorialTail(n - 1, n * accumulator);
}
```

### Tree Traversal

```csharp
static void Traverse(TreeNode node)
{
    if (node == null) return;
    Console.WriteLine(node.Value);
    Traverse(node.Left);
    Traverse(node.Right);
}
```

### Directory Traversal

```csharp
static void ListFiles(string path, string indent = "")
{
    foreach (var file in Directory.GetFiles(path))
        Console.WriteLine($"{indent}{Path.GetFileName(file)}");

    foreach (var dir in Directory.GetDirectories(path))
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{indent}[{Path.GetFileName(dir)}]");
        ListFiles(dir, indent + "  ");
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Always ensure a base case exists to prevent infinite recursion. Deep recursion can cause StackOverflowException. Consider iterative solutions for performance-critical code. Recursion is ideal for tree-like data structures and divide-and-conquer algorithms.

### Recursion Depth Warnings

```csharp
// Will cause stack overflow for large n
static int BadFactorial(int n) => n <= 1 ? 1 : n * BadFactorial(n - 1);
// Factorial(100000) will crash
```

codeExample:
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Factorial of 5: {Factorial(5)}");
        Console.WriteLine($"Fibonacci of 10: {Fibonacci(10)}");
        Console.WriteLine($"Sum of 1-100: {Sum(100)}");
    }

    static int Factorial(int n) => n <= 1 ? 1 : n * Factorial(n - 1);

    static int Fibonacci(int n) => n <= 1 ? n : Fibonacci(n - 1) + Fibonacci(n - 2);

    static int Sum(int n) => n <= 0 ? 0 : n + Sum(n - 1);
}
